Option B: Generic URL-Path Classifier
Effort: Low-Medium (3-5 days)
Impact: Medium - covers many sites without domain-specific code

Instead of domain-specific classifiers, create a generic URL-path analyzer:

/watch, /video, /play → likely video content
/article, /post, /blog → likely reading content
/search, /results → browsing/navigation
/shorts, /reels, /stories → short-form content (usually distracting)
/learn, /course, /tutorial → educational
Combine with title analysis for better accuracy.

Option C: Screen Capture + Vision LLM
Effort: High (2-4 weeks)
Impact: Very High - true "agent watching screen"

Periodically capture screen and send to vision LLM:

"Is this screen showing productive work or distraction?"
"What is the user doing right now?"
Works for any application, not just browser
Challenges:

Privacy concerns (screen capture)
Cost (vision API calls)
Latency (can't block in real-time)
Local LLM option needed for privacy
Use case: Background monitoring + logging, not real-time blocking

Option D: Rule Evolution System
Effort: Medium (1-2 weeks)
Impact: High for long-term intelligence

Build a feedback loop:

Log all classifications with context
Track user overrides (user said "this is productive" when we said "distraction")
Periodic analysis - LLM reviews logs and suggests rule updates
Rule versioning - Track rule changes over time
Example flow:

User overrides block on "youtube.com/watch?v=xyz" (title: "Python Tutorial")
→ System logs: "User marked EDUCATION, we said ENTERTAINMENT"
→ Weekly analysis: "User frequently overrides for 'tutorial' in title"
→ Suggested rule: "Add 'tutorial' to education_keywords"
→ User approves → Rule updated
